## Document Conversion

### HTML to PDF

**Most common use case** - Generate PDFs from HTML templates.

**Pattern**:
1. Prepare HTML content with CSS styling
2. Send HTML to Gotenberg via POST
3. Receive PDF response

**Best practices**:
- Use inline CSS or embedded styles (external stylesheets may not load)
- Test with different page sizes (A4, Letter, custom)
- Set margins appropriately
- Include all assets inline (images as base64)

**Example HTML structure**:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <style>
    body { font-family: Arial, sans-serif; margin: 0; padding: 20px; }
    .header { font-size: 24px; font-weight: bold; }
    .footer { position: absolute; bottom: 0; width: 100%; }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <div class="header">Invoice #12345</div>
  <p>Content here...</p>
  <div class="footer">Page 1</div>
</body>
</html>
```

### URL to PDF

**Convert live web pages to PDF**.

**Pattern**:
1. Provide URL to Gotenberg
2. Gotenberg renders page with Chromium
3. Returns PDF

**Best practices**:
- Ensure URL is accessible from Gotenberg server
- Set appropriate wait time for dynamic content
- Consider authentication if URL requires it
- Use print-friendly stylesheets (@media print)

**Performance note**: Slower than HTML to PDF (needs to fetch resources).

### Office Documents to PDF

**Convert Office formats** (DOCX, XLSX, PPTX) to PDF.

**Pattern**:
1. Upload Office document
2. LibreOffice converts to PDF
3. Receive PDF response

**Supported formats**:
- Word: `.docx`, `.doc`, `.odt`
- Excel: `.xlsx`, `.xls`, `.ods`
- PowerPoint: `.pptx`, `.ppt`, `.odp`

**Limitations**:
- Complex macros may not convert correctly
- Embedded objects may render differently
- Conversion slower than HTML to PDF

### Markdown to PDF

**Convert Markdown to PDF** via HTML intermediate.

**Pattern**:
1. Convert Markdown to HTML (client-side or server-side)
2. Send HTML to Gotenberg
3. Receive PDF

**Tip**: Use a Markdown library with CSS styling for professional output.

