## Anti-Patterns

### ❌ Large HTML Payloads

```
BAD: Sending MB-sized HTML with embedded images
GOOD: Optimize images, use compression, split documents
```

**Why**: Large payloads slow conversion and may exceed size limits.

### ❌ Synchronous Generation

```
BAD: Blocking API call until PDF is ready
GOOD: Async pattern with job queue
```

**Why**: Long conversions block application threads and degrade UX.

### ❌ External Resource Dependencies

```
BAD: HTML with external CSS/images (may fail to load)
GOOD: Inline all styles and base64-encode images
```

**Why**: Gotenberg may not have access to external resources (network isolation, auth).

### ❌ No Error Handling

```
BAD: Assuming conversion always succeeds
GOOD: Handle timeout, size limit, and format errors
```

**Why**: Conversions can fail for many reasons (invalid HTML, timeout, resource limits).

### ❌ Unbounded Retries

```
BAD: Infinite retries on failure
GOOD: Exponential backoff with max retries (3-5)
```

**Why**: Repeated failures indicate a persistent issue, not a transient error.

### ❌ Missing Timeouts

```
BAD: No timeout on conversion requests
GOOD: Set appropriate timeouts (30-60s)
```

**Why**: Hung requests can exhaust resources.

### ❌ Ignoring PDF Size

```
BAD: Generating massive PDFs (hundreds of pages)
GOOD: Paginate or split into multiple PDFs
```

**Why**: Large PDFs are slow to generate, transfer, and render.

